The universe is thus an emanation from the deity, the connection between the two still of course subsisting. We may regard it as a body, in which the deity is present as the animating soul. But we must not be misled into considering the deity only as the soul of the universe3 it is rather only a part of the original deity that is embodied in the universe23 the deity does not itself for that cease to exist, exalted above the universe3 it is not simply imma- nent, it is also transcendent. The divine ether mingled with no grosser stuff encircles the world that has proceeded frorn it, from it soul and life continually flow forth into the world, without its ever being exhausted3 the grosser elements rather, out of which the cor- poreal world has been formed, will all gradually be dissolved by it and absorbed into it; the world returns to the deity, to come forth again from it anew.3
